WEBVTT

00:00.031 --> 00:02.234
people who maybe have never heard this.

00:03.055 --> 00:13.447
In your every cell, you have this thing called DNA, which basically is an encoding of all of your biological functions.

00:13.547 --> 00:17.251
Now, usually biological functions are realized through proteins.

00:17.752 --> 00:22.798
So DNA is basically a building plan for all of your proteins.

00:22.778 --> 00:25.282
This happens in the following two steps.

00:25.403 --> 00:30.031
First, there is this transcription step where RNA is built.

00:30.051 --> 00:35.440
This is basically a copy of your DNA, but is only single strand, as you can see right here.

00:36.462 --> 00:42.913
And then there is a translation step that finally translates the RNA into the protein.

00:42.893 --> 00:47.742
What will end up is just a sequence of these beads right here.

00:48.202 --> 00:50.947
Now these beads are what are called amino acids.

00:51.108 --> 00:55.475
So a protein is simply a chain of these amino acids.

00:55.495 --> 01:04.952
There are 20 different amino acids and the order of these amino acids in the chain makes the function of the protein.

01:04.932 --> 01:13.420
Now specifically we know about these proteins that it seems to be very important how their three-dimensional shape is.

01:13.860 --> 01:18.244
So a lot of these different amino acids have different chemical properties.

01:18.284 --> 01:22.648
Some are sort of, I think, negatively charged.

01:22.808 --> 01:24.230
Some are neutral.

01:24.430 --> 01:26.252
Some are acids and so on.

01:26.312 --> 01:28.614
So they have very different chemical properties.

01:28.754 --> 01:33.218
So once you build this protein and you kind of release it into the cell,

01:33.198 --> 01:36.682
it will curl up into a three-dimensional structure.

01:36.742 --> 01:58.564
So this one might be, you know, doing something like this and sort of form a circle or something like this just because these proteins here, they kind of attract each other maybe electrically and thus the protein forms a circle and the function of the protein is very much related to its shape.

01:58.544 --> 02:03.652
So, if it is a circle, it could maybe, you know, trap something else in here.

02:04.013 --> 02:07.158
So, you really have to think of these things like kind of tools.

02:07.799 --> 02:21.480
There are proteins that cut other proteins and they are really shaped sort of like a scissor that exactly fits these other proteins such that you can effectively cut them.

02:21.460 --> 02:28.432
So sometimes you can substitute an amino acid for a different amino acid like this here.

02:29.273 --> 02:34.221
If it doesn't change the shape, very often you're fine.

02:34.241 --> 02:37.647
The protein function isn't changed.

02:37.627 --> 02:47.696
but if you change a different amino acid that is sort of vital to the shape and the shape changes, then your protein very often loses function.

02:47.716 --> 03:06.132
So mutations in DNA sometimes lead to mutations in protein, not always because there is some redundancy in this in this translation step from RNA, but if they do lead to a different amino acid, it doesn't actually mean that the function changes.

03:06.472 --> 03:07.633
So

03:07.613 --> 03:16.865
there is sort of value in analyzing the sequence of the structure of proteins rather than the structure of DNA.

03:16.925 --> 03:36.051
Of course, it's also important to analyze the structure of DNA, but it is also, it is equally important to analyze the structure of proteins because they, not all the information is in the sequence, not all the obvious information is in the sequence.

03:36.031 --> 03:40.050
So what does this paper do this paper goes?

